    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-02-19T13:14:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-02-19T13:14:00-05:00" n="392"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d392">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 822.00/360.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Minister <persName type="from">Hartman</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegrams.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Quito</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-02-19T13:00:00-05:14">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 19, 1914, 1 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Answering your February 14, 6 p.m. I have diligently endeavored to obtain a
                    statement of American interests at Esmeraldas in danger from revolution which a
                    war vessel would protect but without results. I based my recommendation for a
                    war vessel largely upon a telegram from American Minister at Lima dated February
                    13, 3 p.m., which stated: “Immediate steps should be taken at Esmeraldas. Will
                    the Department send a cruiser there, and when? Anxious about cable operatives.”
                    Lima has better telegraphic communication with Esmeraldas than Quito.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hartman</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
